":mtgtip:`Research<Research // Development>`, :mtgtip:`Ring of Ma'ruf`) do"
" not function in Commander unless the optional sideboard rule is in use. "
"If sideboards are used, wishes and similar cards may retrieve sideboard "
"cards."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:126
msgid "Partial Paris Mulligan rule"
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:128
msgid ""
"Because Commander games are long and usually not played in multigame "
"matches, the format uses a modified mulligan rule designed to alleviate "
"mana-light hands without significantly increasing the odds of finding "
"individual cards. This is also known as the \"Brittany\" mulligan rule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:130
msgid ""
"In turn order, players may exile (face down) some or all of the cards in "
"their hand."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:131
msgid ""
"Each player then draws one less card from their deck than the number they"
" exiled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:132
msgid ""
"Players who exiled at least one card may return to step 1 and repeat the "
"process, drawing one less card each time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:133
msgid "Players shuffle all exiled cards into their deck."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:135
msgid ""
"It is worth noting that even with this form of mulligan, decks playing an"
" insufficient number of mana sources will routinely draw poor hands or "
"insufficient mana as the game progresses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:139
msgid "Optional rules for Commander"
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:141
msgid ""
"Commander is designed first and foremost for social players. It cannot be"
" all things to all people."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:143
msgid ""
"Nevertheless, many people like to play for prizes or other non-social "
"incentives. Those incentives can help build communities and playgroups, "
"but they can also undermine the social contract which keeps the format "
"balanced."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:145
msgid ""
"When running a competitive commander event, the recommended list of cards"
" to avoid (under the primary deckbuilding rules) is one place to start. "
"It is not however, nor is it intended to be, comprehensive. There are a "
"great many uninteresting uses for the cards not listed there, and "
"additional structure is required to keep degeneracy [#f1]_ in check. To "
"that end, a selection of optional rules are provided here for prospective"
" TOs or players who find their playgroup can't find a balance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:149
msgid "Sideboards"
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:151
msgid ""
"Rather than filling every deck with banal responses, it is preferable to "
"allow some flexibility in the composition of a deck."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:153
msgid ""
"Players may bring a 10 card sideboard in addition to their 99 cards and 1"
" Commander."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:154
msgid ""
"After Commanders are announced, players have 3 minutes to make 1-for-1 "
"substitutions to their deck."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:155
msgid "Any cards not played as part of the deck may be retrieved by \"wishes\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:158
msgid "Reasoning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:160
msgid ""
"Highly tuned threats piloted by skilled opponents mandate efficient "
"answers. The minimum number of response cards required to ensure they are"
" available in the early turns can easily overwhelm the majority of an EDH"
" deck's building space."
msgstr ""

#: ../../commander.rst:162
msgid ""
"Sideboards allow players to respond to the \"best\" strategies in a "
"timely fashion . They should be strongly considered as a necessary "
"defense against brokenness and degeneracy in an environment where no "
"gentlemans agreement on style of play exists."
msgstr ""

